[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to The Course"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ About me:  I am a 35 years old FIDE Master from Novosibirsk, Russia. I started playing chess early, at the age of 5, and won a lot of local trophies. Then I had a break from it after completing my Master's degree in economics and got back to it only after several years. I achieved FIDE Master level  (2305)  during the tournament in Montenegro in 2019.   My daughter Alice is also a chess player, and I coached her when she became the champion of Siberia among girls under 9 years old in 2017. I have a lot of students and most of them progress rapidly, especially 2 girls and a boy from the UK, who are top players of their age group in the UK.  About the course:  Kan is a rare variation of Sicilian Defense, Najdorf or Dragon variations are more common. But the Kan Sicilian Variation is played in order to achieve the position, in which white will have difficulty with the orientation. At the same time, black has the opportunity to gain the initiative in case of White’s mistake.   Of course, if white plays without any mistakes, the most black can do is to make the position even. But the position is difficult and there is always a chance of making a mistake, just as in any other opening. That’s when black pieces can open up and start interacting, and a counter-play emerges especially on a c-file.   This opening is played by club players, grandmasters and even by top grandmasters. For example, such GMs as Fabiano Caruana play this opening with black - it’s his main opening. Many other players also use it, for example, Vishy Anand, Vladimir Kramnik, Sergey Rublevsky, Veselin Topalov and even Magnus Carlsen.   Fabiano Caruana is outstanding, because a lot of his games illustrate using this opening very well and show how black uses white’s mistakes. Chess players with a rating of 2700 play this opening in order to create a complicated position for chess players with a rating of 2500 and lower.   In case you’re playing with a rating a little bit lower than yours and you want to play for a win with black, that is the opening you need.   Also, it should be a part of your main repertoire. Paulsen variation and Taimanov variation could be an addition to Kan Variation, allowing them to switch from one position to another. It’s enough to know how to play Kan and get good positions though.   Why have I decided to record a course devoted to this variation? I enjoy playing sharp, complicated and unclear positions, particularly Sicilian Defense. I am ready to play any Sicilian with white, but if we are speaking about black, then I would prefer Kan Sicilian, of course.   I have lost many games with black Kan Sicilian, and each time I lost, made me think that I need to study this variation better. I needed to find out where I made mistakes, what I didn’t understand and what I did wrong. Of course, when playing with black pieces I understood more than my opponents, and I was losing due to some insignificant mistakes, miscalculations or a lack of time. When I was in time trouble, I had to make weak moves not to go over the timing.   But nevertheless, I analyzed the whole game and looked for the moves that I could improve, where I should have used another plan, where I made mistakes, what I didn’t understand and moved the pieces. That is how I have become an expert in Kan Sicilian.   At the same time, during the analysis of the positions with an engine that I conducted, I have studied the literature and recommendations of grandmasters. In particular, I have consulted with GM Dmitry Bocharov who plays this variation regularly.   He also gave me advice on what games to watch and which players to look up to. There is not much literature dedicated to this variation, and I have read 80% of all of it. I have concluded that you can find mistakes in every book.   That is why in this course I have tried to cover the inaccuracies that could be found in books with the examples from my own experience and analysis that can help you to play this variation without any hesitation.   It is important to mention that the knowledge of the variation only is not that useful. You have to be good at calculation, understand the position well and make the moves on time.   Description of the moves:    1.e4  - traditionally the most popular move for white Black answers with  1...c5    The Sicilian Defense is the sharpest and safest way to fight against 1.e4 and also the most popular. If you play for a win, it is the variation for you.   The second move could be  2.c3  or  2.Nc3  ,  but most commonly it is  2.Nf3  e6  with the idea to control d5. e6 move means that if black controls d5, then they can’t control e5 with the pawns, at least in the beginning of the game.   That is why black’s plan is to control e5 with pieces, for example, make such moves as Qd8-c7 or Nb8-c6. White usually answers with  3.d4  ,  and then we have open Sicilian Defense. Of course, there are many options, you could also play 3.c3 or 3.g3.  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  4...a6  The idea behind the move is not to let Knight on b5 or in certain cases, Bishop on b5 and secure the position of the black Queen on c7, because it guards the e5-square.   Also 4...a6 move allows us to play extended fianchetto of the white bishop and later play b7-b5 and lead the bishop to b7. That is a typical position that happens in most games where black plays Kan Sicilian and there are many options here. For example,  5.Nc3  ,  5.c4  ,  5.Be2  ,  or  5.Bd3  I explain all of these moves in my course. I hope that you will learn about this opening despite its complexity. For example, it’s not like London Variation where you remember the moves, but almost don’t care about their order.   Here in Kan Sicilian, you need to know some variations move-to-move and only then you are going to be successful at variation. But believe me: if you have completed this course, you will know way more than your opponent. Knowing Kan Sicilian, you will be able to get the advantage at the very beginning of your game.  Conclusion:  I give a full overview of options against each move and explain my choices, and sometimes I offer more than one solution: for tactical and strategic players.  In modern chess, when the chess theory in the most popular variations is well known to most chess players, advanced theorists try to step aside and get the position that they are ready to play, and for which their opponents are absolutely not ready. Even if there is no advantage, but this position should be clear to you.  Kan Sicilian is still a rather rare and insufficiently studied opening  (compared to, for example, Najdorf, Dragon or Sveshnikov Variations)  . So use your chance to study a decent opening for black and get familiar and understandable positions.  I am sure this will be useful for players of absolutely all levels, especially if you have suddenly decided to change your opening repertoire. I am also sure that this course will be useful for those who would like to learn how to play white against Kan Sicilian. }
