1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. f4
{ White plays 3.f4 to initiate the attack on the kingside. One of the White options is to transpose to the Grand Prix Attack. However, an early f-pawn move has its own disadvantages. And Black proves it by opening the position up in the center. }
3... d5 4. g3 Nc6 5. Bg2 d4
{ To get control over the center and gain a tempo!  5...dxe4  is another possible option.  6.Nxe4  Be7  7.Nf3  Nf6  8.Nf2  O-O  9.O-O  Qc7  10.b3  b6= }
6. Nce2 d3 7. cxd3 Nb4 { It's much better to take this pawn with a knight! } 8.
d4
{ White suffers from a lack of development and decides to give back the extra pawn because Black's d4-pawn is a potential weakness. }
8... cxd4 9. Nf3 Nd3+ 10. Kf1 Nf6 { Attacking on e4 and keeping Ng4 in mind. }
11. Qa4+
{ If  11.Nfxd4?  e5!  12.fxe5  Ng4  threatening the Ndf2 fork  13.Qc2  Ngxe5-+  White can hardly develop their pieces, the king is weak and Black is threatening 14...Qf6+. }
11... Bd7 { Black also wants to join the bishop by playing Bd7-b5. } 12. Qxd4
Bb5 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. e5 Ng4
{ With more than enough compensation. All of Black's pieces can participate in the attack. }
