[Black "3.b3 with 5.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. Be2 { A logical move, but too slow for this position. } 5... Nf6 6. e5 Nd5
{ The bishop on e2 becomes the object of the attack after Black occupies the f4-square with their knight. }
7. O-O Nf4 8. Re1 Be7
{ The f4-knight is better than White's light-squared bishop. } 9. Bf1 f6
{ Undermining the center and trading White's good bishop on b2. } 10. d3 O-O
11. Nbd2 Ng6 { This is how Black forces White to trade on f6. } 12. exf6 Bxf6
13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Ne4 Qe7
{ To protect the c5-pawn. Later the queen can be relocated to f7. Now White's knight in the center becomes the object of the attack. This allows Black to occupy the center with their pawns and gain a tempo. }
15. c4 d5 16. cxd5 exd5
{ There is no discovered attack with the e4-knight. Black achieved almost a dream position with Bc8-g4 and Ra8-e8 as their next moves. }
