[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. a3 d5
{ White is slow with their development. That's why Black decides to open up the position immediately! }
5. e5
{ White plans to keep a closed position intending to initiate a kingside attack which is a typical plan for positions with French pawn structure. However, black has an effective weapon to prevent it! }
5... Nc6 6. axb4 Bxb4 7. c3 Be7 8. d4
{ White built their pawn chain intending to start an attack on the kingside. }
8... Bd7
{ This move illustrates the key idea of Black's strategy in this opening. Trading light-squared bishops condemns White's kingside attack. }
9. Bd3 Rc8 10. O-O a6
{ Black should reach this or a similar position in the Wing Gambit. The move order doesn't make much difference. It's much more important to understand the plan. Black should play Nc6-a7 and then Bd7-b5. As for the g8-knight, let's wait for an opportunity to develop it to h6. While the center is closed, we can keep the king on e8 and focus on attacking the c3-pawn. }
11. Nfd2 { White blocks the c1-h6 diagonal. } 11... Nh6
{ White blocks the c1-h6 diagonal. } 12. Nb3 Nf5 13. Ba3 Bxa3 14. Rxa3 Rc7
{ Prophylaxis! } 15. Qe2 Na7
{ With the idea to trade light-squared bishops and attack the c3-pawn with Na7-b5! }
16. Nc5 Bb5
{ Black focuses on the queenside where they have a pawn majority. After making preparations, Black can play b7-b6, sacrifice the a6-pawn, and capture the weakness on c3 to open up the position. }
