1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ With this plan, White's only plan is to fianchetto their light-squared bishop and stick to a King's Indian Attack setup. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...d5  is another possible option here. But it's often that Black combines Nc6 and d5 ideas. Moreover, it makes more sense to play Nb8-c6, while White's light-squared bishop is restricted and there is no Bf1-b5 option. }
4. g3 d5
{ Black gains space in the center and provokes White to defend the e4-pawn, because this endgame after trading on e4 is in Black's favor. }
5. Nbd2 Bd6 { to secure the e5-square and to locate the g-knight to e7. } 6.
Bg2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O { Black leads in development and has more center control. }
8. Nh4
{ A typical move for the King's Indian Attack with the idea to use the f-pawn to fight for the center or continue the attack with f4-f5. }
8... b6 9. f4 f6
{ Black keeps their pawn flexible, to counter any of White's plans. } 10. Re1
Bc7 11. c3 a5
{ A tempo-battle with approximately equal chances for both sides. Black's plan on the queenside is connected to the b-pawn march, while White tries to create problems for the Black king on the kingside. }
