1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3 is a traditional weapon against the Kan Sicilian. This move is quite popular among club players and grandmasters. }
5... Bc5
{ The most playable variation. Black has some other options including  5...g6  but if Black wants to play for a victory, 5...Bc5 is the best choice. Positions that may happen in this line are so complicated that any mistake made by White can result into a winning chance for Black. }
6. Nb3 Ba7
{ 6...Be7  is another popular option, but after  7.Qg4  attacking g7. White gets the initiative and the Black bishop on e7 is less active than if it was on a7. Black sets up an ambush with this bishop on a7. }
7. Qg4
{ One of the most dangerous ideas for Black. White threatens to take the pawn, but the other idea is to keep the queen on g3 from where it puts pressure on g7 and controls the e5-square. }
7... Nf6 8. Qxg7 { Too risky at this exact moment. } 8... Rg8 9. Qh6 Bxf2+
{ Gaining a pawn back. If the White king captures the bishop, Black forks on g4! }
10. Kd1 e5
{ Slow, but effective. Black wants their light-squared bishop to enter the game. }
11. Rf1 Rg6 { Black gains a tempo and protects the f6-knight as well. } 12. Qd2
Ba7 { Black is slightly better due to White's king position. } *

