1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3 is a traditional weapon against the Kan Sicilian. This move is quite popular among club players and grandmasters. }
5... Bc5
{ The most playable variation. Black has some other options including  5...g6  but if Black wants to play for a victory, 5...Bc5 is the best choice. Positions that may happen in this line are so complicated that any mistake made by White can result into a winning chance for Black. }
6. Nb3 Ba7
{ 6...Be7  is another popular option, but after  7.Qg4  @@StartBracket@@attacking g7@@EndBracket@@ White gets the initiative and the Black bishop on  e7  is less active than if it was on  a7  . Black sets up an ambush with this bishop on  a7  . }
7. Qe2 Nc6 8. Be3 d6
{ A flexible move. First of all, Black controls the e5-square. And, secondly, Black intends to relocate their rook from a7 to d7 in some lines. }
9. O-O { White may castle first intending to play the Maroczy Bind. } 9... Nge7
10. c4
{ Maroczy Bind strategies are quite popular nowadays. And this move definitely offers more options for White, but at the same time weakens the d4-square. }
10... e5 11. Nc3 Nd4 { White can't tolerate an enemy knight in the center. }
12. Bxd4 exd4 13. Nd5 O-O { Finishing development. } 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Qd2 Bd7
{ Black threatens to play b7-b5 to get rid of the c4-pawn, then to play d6-d5, trade the other pawn in the center, and support the passed pawn on the d-file. Bd7-c6 and Ra8-e8 is another possible setup for Black in this position. }
