[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Alapin with 7.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a common weapon against the Sicilian Defense for those who don't want to learn much  theory or prefer a more positional playing style. }
2... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4
{ White may vary the move order: 4.d4, 4.Bc4 and 4.Nf3 can be played as well and all lead to the same line. Deviations from the main line only favor Black. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. cxd4 e6
{ 6...e6 is one of the main options for Black.  6...d6  is another popular option, for example. But if Black decides to follow the Kan Sicilian, they may reach this position with an absolutely different move order. That's why it's highly recommended to stick to the same strategy every time. A high-level player, of course, may learn several possible lines here and vary them from time to time. }
7. Nc3 { An attempt to deviate from the main line! } 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 d6
{ White has to take on d6, otherwise Black captures on e5 and gets a better pawn structure. White gets almost nothing if they try to support the e5-pawn here. }
9. exd6 Bxd6
{ This is a typical pawn structure with c3+d4. Black should neutralize White's activity on the kingside, pressure the c3+d4 pair on the queenside, and blockade on the dark squares. This is how Black can take over the initiative and play for a victory. }
10. Bd3 h6
{ Black will need to keep a constant lookout for the Bd3xh7 sacrifice if they don't play h7-h6. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Qe2 Ne7
{ To block the b1-h7 diagonal with Ne7-g6 in case of Qe2-e4. } 13. h4
{ White wants to initiate an attack, but plays too adventurously. A aggressive setup by Black prevents White's activity. Instead, a more sound alternative for Black is to play in the center. }
13... Qc7 14. Re1 b6
{ Black is not afraid of  15.Qe4   14...Qxc3  is another possible option, but it seems to be too risky, especially when Black's main priority is to finish the development of their bad bishop. }
15. Qe4 f5 16. Qxa8 Bd7 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8
{ The position of dynamic equilibrium. Black can even sacrifice the pawn to be able to activate their pieces and obtain the initiative. Black’s task is more to focus on White’s weaknesses such as the c3-pawn. A kingside attack is still possible, however, Black is unlikely to checkmate with just a few minor pieces on the board. }
