1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. Nge2 a6
{ Another move that is possible here is  3...Nc6  However, White may play  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  and Black gets a slightly different type of position with the knight standing on c6 @@StartBracket@@instead of a pawn on a6@@EndBracket@@. This position happens in the Taimanov Sicilian @@StartBracket@@or Paulsen Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ and requires knowledge of many different lines. But if Black prefers Kan Sicilian positions more, then 3...a6 is really what they need. It's not about the move order, it's more about the type of pawn structure. }
4. g3
{ If not  4.d4  then 4.g3 which supports two different plans: a kingside attack and d2-d4 in the future. }
4... Qc7
{ This is another typical Kan Sicilian move. We keep the queen on c7 to secure the e5-square. The a6-pawn prevents the White knight from coming to b5 to harass the queen. }
