3. Nge2 a6
{ Another move that is possible here is  3...Nc6  However, White may play  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  and Black gets a slightly different type of position with the knight standing on c6 @@StartBracket@@instead of a pawn on a6@@EndBracket@@. This position happens in the Taimanov Sicilian @@StartBracket@@or Paulsen Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ and requires knowledge of many different lines. But if Black prefers Kan Sicilian positions more, then 3...a6 is really what they need. It's not about the move order, it's more about the type of pawn structure. }
4. g3
{ If not  4.d4  then 4.g3 which supports two different plans: a kingside attack and d2-d4 in the future. }
4... Qc7
{ This is another typical Kan Sicilian move. We keep the queen on c7 to secure the e5-square. The a6-pawn prevents the White knight from coming to b5 to harass the queen. }
5. Bg2 Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Be7
{ In the Kan Sicilian, the dark-squared bishop is usually on e7 or b4. On d6, it can be the object of an attack after Ndb5. And the bishop on c5 would prevent any future play on the c-file for Black. }
8. O-O d6
{ The position is equal. Black has a flexible pawn center and the only Black piece that needs improvement is the light-squared bishop. Of course, Black's plan depends on what White does. }
9. a4 Nc6 { Black provokes White to make a decision: capture or retreat. } 10.
Nb3 b6
{ With no knight on d4, Black shouldn't be afraid of e4-e5 and take their time to develop their worst minor piece. b6 also prevents White from playing a5. }
11. f4 Bb7 12. Be3 O-O { Finishing our development. } 13. g4
{ White's attack looks strong because of more space on the kingside, but Black has no weaknesses while having active pieces and a flexible pawn structure. }
13... d5 14. g5 { Provokes Black to capture on e4. } 14... Nxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4
16. Bxe4 Nb4
{ After trading light-squared bishops, White can't progress with the attack. Moreover, the center is open. The Black pieces are more active and the Black rook will dominate on the d- and c-files. }
