{ The position is equal. Black has a flexible pawn center and the only Black piece that needs improvement is the light-squared bishop. Of course, Black's plan depends on what White does. }
9. Be3 O-O 10. f4 Nc6 { 10...b5  is too risky due to  11.e5 } 11. Nb3
{ By playing with their knight to b3, White loses a tempo and Black is fine now. Even black can be better after a few more moves. }
11... b5 12. a3 Bb7
{ White's plan here is to advance the g-pawn to g5, get the queen to h5, and make a rook lift. But it's quite difficult to execute all these moves with the open center. As for Black, they want to relocate the bishop to g7 and make a break in the center to get counterplay. Black may also exploit the semi-open c-file. }
