1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 Qc7
{ 4...b5  definitely deserves attention with the idea to fianchetto a light-squared bishop immediately. However, it's too many moves with the pawns and the analysis showed that 4...Qc7 is a more solid continuation. Still the same idea - to secure the e5-spot and start kingside development with Nf6. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. O-O d6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Be7
{ And finally we came to the same position, that was analyzed after 3.Nge2 a6 4.g3 Qc7. }
