[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack with 4.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. f4
{ White plays 3.f4 to initiate the attack on the kingside. One of the White options is to transpose to the Grand Prix Attack. However, an early f-pawn move has its own disadvantages. And Black proves it by opening the position up in the center. }
3... d5 { after } 4. d3 Nc6
{ Black is practically a tempo up compared to variations with 4...a6. } 5. Nf3
Nf6
{ Another option for Black here is to get the game into the endgame after  5...dxe4  6.dxe4  Qxd1  7.Nxd1  Nf6=  However, if you prefer more complicated positions, 5...Nf6 is a good alternative here keeping in mind the idea to trade queens later or even avoid it. }
6. e5 Nd7
{ 6...d4 is another option in this position. For example,  6...d4  7.Ne4  Nxe4  8.dxe4  Be7  9.Bd3=  However, 6...Nd7 is more flexible. If now White decides to support the center with d3-d4, the position will transpose to the French Defense @@StartBracket@@without a tempo for White@@EndBracket@@. }
7. g3 b5
{ Saving a tempo on a7-a6. Of course, the pawn is not hanging. If  8.Nxb5  Qa5  9.Nc3  d4!  and Black gains a piece. }
8. Bg2 b4 9. Ne2 a5 10. O-O Be7
{ Black has a space advantage on the queenside and keeps playing there! } 11.
g4 Qb6 12. Ng3 Bb7 13. Be3 a4
{ Keeping the attack on the queenside. Black doesn't castle while waiting for what White is going to play and keeps flexibility. Black can castle to any side. }
14. Qe2 a3 15. b3 O-O-O
{ Now when the position is closed, it's safe to castle queenside! Black can keep playing on the queenside relocating pieces to better positions and wait until White opens the position! If White doesn't do this, Black can switch to the kingside. }
