1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. f4
{ White plays 3.f4 to initiate the attack on the kingside. One of the White options is to transpose to the Grand Prix Attack. However, an early f-pawn move has its own disadvantages. And Black proves it by opening the position up in the center. }
3... d5 4. Bb5+ { Another possible option for White. } 4... Bd7
{ But Black is happy to exchange their light-squared bishop! } 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ Black's knight is better located on c6 @@StartBracket@@from that square it attacks the key-square on d4@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Nf3 dxe4 7. Ne5 Qc7 8. Qe2 Nf6 9. Nxe4 Be7
{ There is no need to take on e4 and allow White to activate the queen. } 10.
Qb5+ Nbd7
{ White's e4-knight is hanging and the most natural move for them is to trade pieces. }
11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Nxd7
{ Black was threatening a7-a6 and b7-b5, so White had to take on d7. } 12...
Qxd7 13. Qxc5 Rc8
{ This is how Black takes over the initiative and ruins White's pawn structure. The b2-pawn will also be the object of an attack after Rc8xc2. }
