[White "Chapter 1: 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack with 4.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ This move is mostly played by those who want to play the Kan Variation. Black is threatening to play d7-d5. The kingside attack with f2-f4 is not really promising against an early ...d5 by Black. Instead, White should fight Black for central control. }
3. f4
{ White plays 3.f4 to initiate the attack on the kingside. One of the White options is to transpose to the Grand Prix Attack. However, an early f-pawn move has its own disadvantages. And Black proves it by opening the position up in the center. }
3... d5 4. Nf3 dxe4
{ 4...Nc6  leads to more complicated positions and is recommended for those who have French Defense experience, because some of the ideas there are quite similar. For example, Nge7-f5 and f7-f6. However, 4...dxe4 leads to  simpler positions where White has only a few ideas and it's easy for Black to neutralize them! }
5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ The e6-pawn restricts the light-squared bishop's activity in such positions. That's why trading these bishops is usually in Black's favor! }
7. Nxe4 Nc6 8. O-O O-O-O 9. Qe2 f5
{ A crucial decision! But this move allows Black to fight for the key-square @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@ in the center, while the potential weakness of the e6-pawn can't be exploited. }
10. Neg5 Re8 11. b3 h6 12. Nh3 Bd6
{ White wants to occupy the e5-square, but Black is happy to trade their dark-squared bishop on e5 and locate the other knight on d5. }
13. Bb2 Nf6 *

