5. Be2 { A logical move, but too slow for this position. } 5... Nf6 6. e5 Nd5
{ The bishop on e2 becomes the object of the attack after Black occupies the f4-square with their knight. }
7. O-O Nf4 8. Re1 Be7
{ The f4-knight is better than White's light-squared bishop. } 9. Bf1 f6
{ Undermining the center and trading White's good bishop on b2. } 10. exf6
{ The most natural move that leads to a forced variation } 10... Bxf6 11. Bxf6
Qxf6
{ Black gets center control and only 3 moves left to finish their development. }
12. Nc3 O-O 13. Ne4 Qg6
{ 13.Ne4 is quite attractive, but now with the Black queen on g6, White can't capture on c5 because of 14...Nh3+ and 15...Nf2+ fork. In this position, Black may choose how to place their pawns in the center depending on what White does. d7-d5 can be played with the intention to play e6-e5 later or the c5-d6-e5 pawn formation can be played as well. }
