{ Two other alternatives are  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  Nf6   and  3...b6  However, 3...a6 in practice is more helpful. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ 3...Nc6 can be faced with 4.Bb5. It's still playable for black, but requires additional preparation as seen with the move 3...a6. }
5. Be2 d5
{ Black agrees to play the position with an isolated pawn. Piece activity compensates for the weakness of the d5-pawn. For those who want to avoid positions with an isolated pawn, I recommend playing  5...Nf6  6.e5  Nd5  7.O-O  Nf4  8.Re1  d5  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Bf1  O-O  with an approximately equal position. }
6. e5 d4
{ restricting the dark-squared bishop and making the e5-pawn a weakness. } *

