[White "Chapter 2: 3.b3"]
[Black "3.b3 with 5.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. d4
{ The most common move for the Sicilian Defense that becomes more disadvantageous when the bishop is already on b2. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qf6
{ Leads to an open position. But what is more important is that White has to close the diagonal with the c3-pawn. }
7. c3
{ Now the b2-bishop is not so good. However, White hopes to improve it later in the game. }
7... Bc5
{ The best spot for the dark-squared bishop because it pins the knight on d4 to the f2-pawn. }
8. Qd3 Nge7 9. Nd2 O-O
{ Black's light-squared bishop is the only piece left to develop. } 10. g3 d5
{ If  11.exd5  Black captures on d4.  11...Nxd4  12.cxd4  exd5  and the bishop on c5 is not hanging because of the pin on the main diagonal. }
*

