{ Two other alternatives are  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  Nf6   and  3...b6  However, 3...a6 in practice is more helpful. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ 3...Nc6 can be faced with 4.Bb5. It's still playable for black, but requires additional preparation as seen with the move 3...a6. }
5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qf6
{ Pinning the knight! Now white has to play c2-c3 and temporary block their dark-squared bishop. }
7. c3 Bc5 8. Be2 Nge7
{ But not 8...Qg6. In such a case white may castle and sacrifice the e4-pawn, but overtake the initiative! }
9. O-O O-O 10. Na3 d5 11. exd5 exd5
{ Black's piece activity fully compensates for the weakness of the isolated pawn on d5. }
