[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: 3.b3"]
[Black "3.b3 with 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. g3
{ Double fianchetto. Common plan for those who want to get out of book and play a low-theory opening. }
5... d5
{ Black sharpens the position. Instead, Black could stick to a more flexible plan with  5...d6  but in such a case, White adds more pressure to Black's position with 2 fianchettoed bishops. }
6. e5 g5
{ White closed the main diagonal and Black may start active play on the kingside with 2 ideas: to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and threaten the f3-knight. }
7. h3 Bg7 8. Qe2 h6
{ Black wants the g8-knight to join the attack on the e5-pawn, but moving it to e7 immediately cuts off the queen from protecting the g5-pawn. }
9. c3
{ Preparing for d2-d4 to make a pawn chain. That's why the center should be undermined immediately! }
9... f6 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. d4 Nge7
{ A position similar to positions that can arise in the Advance Variation of the French defense. However, here Black is better than in the French positions because of the space gained on the kingside and the the queen's favorable position on f6, where it can support e6-e5.   12.dxc5?  is not good as after  12...e5  threatening e5-e4 and g5-g4 with absolute center control and pressure on the kingside. }
*

