[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. g3
{ Double fianchetto. Common plan for those who want to get out of book and play a low-theory opening. }
5... d5
{ Black sharpens the position. Instead, Black could stick to a more flexible plan with  5...d6  but in such a case, White adds more pressure to Black's position with 2 fianchettoed bishops. }
6. exd5 exd5
{ Black wants to pass the game into the endgame after trading queens. If White doesn't play 7.Qe2, Black plays 7...Qe7+ anyway. }
7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Ngxe7 9. Bg2 Nb4
{ After trading queens, the c2-pawn becomes the object of an attack. } 10. Na3
Bf5 { Developing pieces with tempo! } 11. O-O f6
{ Capturing the c2-pawn could lead to the c5-pawn loss after  11...Nxc2  12.Nxc2  Bxc2  13.Rac1  That's why f7-f6 to restrict White's dark-squared bishop activity. The move also controls the e5-square as well and creates a good spot for the king on f7. }
12. d4 Nec6 { Protecting the c5-pawn with a bishop. } 13. Rfe1+ Kf7 14. Nh4 Be6
15. dxc5 Bxc5
{ And Black's piece activity provides them with a better position. d5-d4 can be played on the next move to restrict White's dark-squared bishop. White would have to play c2-c3 and trade off Black's central pawn. When that happens, Black should be able to activate all their pieces. }
