1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. c4 { The main idea of this move is to prevent black's d7-d5! } 5... Nf6
{ Provoking e4-e5. } 6. e5 Ng4 7. h3 Nh6
{ While White's dark-squared bishop is already on b2, Black is fine to keep the knight on h6. The idea of the Ng8-f6-g4-h6 maneuver was to provoke e4-e5 and then undermine White's center. }
8. Nc3 d6 { White closed the bishop's diagonal and now will have to trade. } 9.
exd6 Bxd6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7
{ 11...Nxd4  allows White to activate the queen. However, 11...Bd7 protects c6. It also overloads or blocks the d-file and allows White to capture the d6-bishop after }
12. Ndb5 axb5 13. Qxd6 Nf5 14. Qf4 e5
{ Another move to gain a tempo and at the same time, restrict White's dark-squared bishop activity. }
15. Qd2 bxc4 16. Bxc4 Ncd4
{ White has a bishop pair, but they can't take advantage of it in this position, especially after Black has occupied the outpost on d4. However, Black needs to be careful about protecting the e5-pawn. An immediate f7-f6 only weakens their position. But f7-f6 can be safely played if the light-squared bishops are exchanged. }
