[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This strategy is supposed to be a dangerous weapon against the Kan Sicilian. White is going to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop and get one more attacker on the e5-square. }
3... a6
{ Of course,  3...Nc6   3...b6   and  3...d6  are other possible options for Black in this position. However,  3...a6  leads to more Kan Sicilian style positions and contains a concrete idea of stopping White's light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ This is where White should select the plan they want to apply and Black has to react accordingly. }
5. Qe2 d6
{ with the idea to close the center with e6-e5 which makes Qd1-e2 a useless move. }
6. g3 e5
{ Black improves their light-squared bishop and restricts white's light-squared bishop. }
7. Bg2 g6
{ Kingside fianchetto is required for black in this position, because white's main plan is c2-c3 and d2-d4. That's why black needs at least one more piece to attack the d4-square. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. c3 Nge7
{ Now Bc8-g4 will be possible after White's planned d2-d4. } 10. d4 exd4 11.
cxd4 Bg4 { Pinning the knight increases the pressure on d4. } 12. dxc5
{ avoiding a pawn loss. } 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nd4
{ with material advantage for Black. The rook is trapped on  a1  after White's best try:  14.Bxd4  Bxd4 }
