1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 a6
{ Two other alternatives are  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  Nf6   and  3...b6  However, 3...a6 in practice is more helpful. }
4. Bb2 Nc6
{ 3...Nc6 can be faced with 4.Bb5. It's still playable for black, but requires additional preparation as seen with the move 3...a6. }
5. Qe2 d6 { to secure the e5-square before playing Ng8-f6 } 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2
Be7 { A typical Scheveningen strategy. } 8. O-O O-O 9. d4
{ White has to play this move. Otherwise, Black may decide to play d6-d5 or e6-e5 to block both bishops! }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7
{ with a pleasant position. White's double fianchetto didn't provide them with any benefits compared to the regular Open Sicilian lines. Black doubles their queen and rook on the c-file and intends to play b7-b5 to take control over the file. }
