[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3: Wing Gambit: 3.b4"]
[Black "4.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. d4
{ The most popular move, but not the strongest one. It allows Black to develop the g8-knight and hinder White's development. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bd3 d6
{ Undermining the center. If speaking about the initiative, it was much better for White to keep their central pawns flexible - on the e4- and d4-squares. However, any pawn move in the center allows Black to undermine it. }
7. O-O dxe5 8. Nxe5 Nd7
{ Offering an exchange. The fewer pieces on the board, the simpler the position becomes. }
9. Nd2 Qc7 10. Re1 Be7
{ Black is a clear pawn up, while White has nothing to impose: their kingside attack is unlikely to succeed. Black's king is still in the center and instead of castling, Black may first play moves such as Qc7-c3 and Nd5-f4 to get rid of White's light-squared bishop. }
*

