{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. d4
{ The most popular move, but not the strongest one. It allows Black to develop the g8-knight and hinder White's development. }
4... Nf6 5. Bd3 d5 6. e5 Ne4
{ This is how Black's knight prevents White's development. } 7. Bxe4
{ is a critical mistake for this position. Now Black has a concrete idea. }
7... dxe4 8. Ng5 Be7 9. Nxe4 Qd5 { The knight is pinned! } 10. f3 Nc6 11. Be3
O-O
{ White gained a pawn back, but due to the Black pawn on b4, they can't play c2-c3 and protect the weakness on d4. }
12. a3 Rd8 { Threatening to take both pawns. } 13. axb4 Nxe5 14. c3
{ to protect the b4-pawn. } 14... Nc4 15. Bf2 b6
{ White was able to equalize the number of pawns, but positionally Black is still better with a bishop pair and better piece activity. }
