1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. d4
{ The most popular move, but not the strongest one. It allows Black to develop the g8-knight and hinder White's development. }
4... Nf6 5. Bd3 d5 6. e5 Ne4
{ This is how Black's knight prevents White's development. } 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3
{ White intends to create a pawn chain - c3-d4-e5 and wants to get rid of the b4-pawn. }
8... f5
{ reinforcing the knight in the center and preventing White's potential attack on the kingside! }
9. exf6 Nxf6
{ 9...gxf6   and  9...Qxf6  are also possible lines, but they require additional analysis. However, 9... Nxf6 is the most solid continuation! }
10. Re1 Bd6
{ Black gets a similar position to what Black achieves in French Defense lines. Their plan is to play e6-e5. }
11. axb4 Nxb4 12. Bb5+ Nc6
{ White wants to trade dark-squared bishops and control the e5-square. This is their only chance to compensate for a pawn loss. There might be compensation, but not more than one pawn. Black intends to finish their development and advance pawns on the queenside or play e6-e5. }
