1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. Bb2
{ With this move, White wants to put additional pressure on Black's kingside. But, it loses a tempo and allows Black to develop the knight to f6. One of the White's best ideas for the Wing Gambit is to play a2-a3 and after Black captures on a3, White's bishop has to take and spend one more tempo. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd5 6. a3
{ White wants to play c2-c4 @@StartBracket@@or c3@@EndBracket@@, but Black's b4-pawn can capture en passant. }
6... Nc6 7. axb4 Bxb4 { Black develops their pieces. } 8. c4 Nb6 9. Be2 d5
{ Simplifying position. Black is a clear pawn up! Their only task is to develop the light-squared bishop on c8 through the c8-h3 diagonal. }
