1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. a3 d5
{ White is slow with their development. That's why Black decides to open up the position immediately! }
5. exd5 Qxd5
{ Of course, the queen should take on d5. As for Black's light-squared bishop, the best option is to fianchetto it and put pressure on the main diagonal! }
6. axb4 Bxb4 7. c3 Be7 8. Na3
{ A typical move for the Alapin Variation can be also played here. The pawn structure is quite similar, but White is already a pawn down. }
8... Nc6 9. Nb5 Qd8
{ Looks like Black's queen loses a tempo, but Na3-b5 doesn't make much sense if the c7-square is well protected. Moreover, Black vacates the d5-square for their g8-knight. }
10. d4 Nf6 11. Bd3 O-O
{ After a7-a6, Ra8-b8, and b7-b5, Black is clearly better. } *

