{ Black should reach this or a similar position in the Wing Gambit. The move order doesn't make much difference. It's much more important to understand the plan. Black should play Nc6-a7 and then Bd7-b5. As for the g8-knight, let's wait for an opportunity to develop it to h6. While the center is closed, we can keep the king on e8 and focus on attacking the c3-pawn. }
11. Ne1 Na7 12. f4
{ The diagonal is blocked. Let's develop the knight and secure the f5-square! }
12... Nh6 13. g4 Nb5
{ Threatening the c3-pawn.  13...Bb5  is another possible alternative for Black. }
14. f5 { If not, Black will play f7-f5! } 14... Bg5
{ And it's not clear how White may develop their attack. White's king can also be in trouble. The position becomes open and Black slowly bring the pieces to defend the king or attack the enemy king through the queenside. In case White captures on e6, Black may secure the f-file with Nh6-f7 and castle kingside afterwards. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3: Wing Gambit: 3.b4"]
[Black "4.a3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ The idea of this pawn sacrifice is to obtain some initiative from the first move and to reduce Black's control over the center. In practice, White has some compensation, but it's not enough to compensate a clear pawn. }
3... cxb4
{ The best way to get the advantage in gambits is to accept the pawn! Those who want to get out of book can play  3...b6  with an unclear position. }
4. a3 d5
{ White is slow with their development. That's why Black decides to open up the position immediately! }
5. e5
{ White plans to keep a closed position intending to initiate a kingside attack which is a typical plan for positions with French pawn structure. However, black has an effective weapon to prevent it! }
5... Nc6 6. axb4 Bxb4 7. c3 Be7 8. d4
{ White built their pawn chain intending to start an attack on the kingside. }
8... Bd7
{ This move illustrates the key idea of Black's strategy in this opening. Trading light-squared bishops condemns White's kingside attack. }
9. Bd3 Rc8 10. O-O a6
{ Black should reach this or a similar position in the Wing Gambit. The move order doesn't make much difference. It's much more important to understand the plan. Black should play Nc6-a7 and then Bd7-b5. As for the g8-knight, let's wait for an opportunity to develop it to h6. While the center is closed, we can keep the king on e8 and focus on attacking the c3-pawn. }
11. Nbd2 Na5
{ To prevent c3-c4. That was what White could play in case of  11...Na7 } 12.
Nb3 Nc4
{ occupying the outpost. There was no sense to trade the knights on b3. The black one is better on c4. }
13. Re1 h5
{ Black can stay in the center for awhile. This move also allows Black to develop their knight to h6! }
14. Nfd2 Bb5
{ White can't capture on c4 with their knight and Black wants to exchange White's light-squared bishop. }
15. Bc2 Nb6
{ While White experiences a lack of space in the center and on the queenside, it doesn't make sense to trade pieces there. }
16. Re3 Qc7
{ Black finishes their development and focuses on the queenside attack by putting more pressure on c3. Nb6-a4 can even be played! }
