1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ With this plan, White's only plan is to fianchetto their light-squared bishop and stick to a King's Indian Attack setup. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...d5  is another possible option here. But it's often that Black combines Nc6 and d5 ideas. Moreover, it makes more sense to play Nb8-c6, while White's light-squared bishop is restricted and there is no Bf1-b5 option. }
4. g3 d5
{ Black gains space in the center and provokes White to defend the e4-pawn, because this endgame after trading on e4 is in Black's favor. }
5. e5
{ Almost never played on the top level, but a typical move for intermediate clubplayers. However, it's a mistake. }
5... Qc7 6. Qe2 f6
{ 6...Nge7  is another possible plan that leads to a better position for Black, but 6...f6 opens the position and allows Black to get the control over the center. In such conditions, there is no shred of active play for White. }
7. Bf4 g5 { winning a pawn. } 8. exf6 gxf4 { without compensation for White. }
