1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ With this plan, White's only plan is to fianchetto their light-squared bishop and stick to a King's Indian Attack setup. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...d5  is another possible option here. But it's often that Black combines Nc6 and d5 ideas. Moreover, it makes more sense to play Nb8-c6, while White's light-squared bishop is restricted and there is no Bf1-b5 option. }
4. g3 d5
{ Black gains space in the center and provokes White to defend the e4-pawn, because this endgame after trading on e4 is in Black's favor. }
5. Qe2 Nge7
{ 5...Nf6  is also possible, but it offers White more attacking chances. } 6.
Bg2 dxe4
{ Black opens the position which drastically reduce the chances of a successful attack for White. }
7. dxe4 Nd4 8. Nxd4 cxd4
{ with this simple exchange, Black equalized the position. } 9. e5 Bd7
{ A sneaky pawn sacrifice. } 10. Bxb7 Rb8 11. Be4 Bb5
{ Forcing White to defend the position. } 12. Bd3 Qd5
{ gaining a tempo and keeping in mind the idea of a queen-and-bishop mate. }
13. O-O Bc6 14. f3 Ng6 { White has no defense for their e5-pawn! } 15. Be4 Bb5
{ If now White's queen moves, the e5-pawn will be taken. } 16. Bxd5 Bxe2 17.
Re1 Bb5 { If now White's bishop escapes to e4, the e5-pawn is lost! } 18. Bb3
h5
{ Black's piece activity compensates for the pawn sacrifice: the light-squared bishop can occupy the main diagonal and the knight moves to e7-f5 in case White plays h2-h4. White's light-squared bishop is quite passive on b3. }
