1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3 is a traditional weapon against the Kan Sicilian. This move is quite popular among club players and grandmasters. }
5... Bc5
{ The most playable variation. Black has some other options including  5...g6  but if Black wants to play for a victory, 5...Bc5 is the best choice. Positions that may happen in this line are so complicated that any mistake made by White can result into a winning chance for Black. }
6. Be3 d6
{ To support the bishop and avoid any tactical ideas with Nd4xe6. But not  6...Qb6?!  which looks attractive @@StartBracket@@double attack@@EndBracket@@, but allows White to overtake the initiative after...  7.c3  Qxb2  8.Nd2  Qxc3  9.Rc1  Qxd3  10.Rxc5  Nc6  11.Qc1  threatening to trap the Black queen with Rc5-c3 and preventing Black from capturing on d4 due to the hanging bishop behind the knight. }
7. O-O Nd7 8. Nd2 Ngf6 9. c4 Ne5
{ Attacking the bishop and hoping for Nf6-g4. } 10. Be2 Bd7 11. f4 Qb6 12. N2b3
Ba4 { Black is still able to gain a piece after f4xe5. } *

