1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3 is a traditional weapon against the Kan Sicilian. This move is quite popular among club players and grandmasters. }
5... Bc5
{ The most playable variation. Black has some other options including  5...g6  but if Black wants to play for a victory, 5...Bc5 is the best choice. Positions that may happen in this line are so complicated that any mistake made by White can result into a winning chance for Black. }
6. c3 d6
{ Black controls the e5-square with such a move as well as keeping their dark-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain. }
7. O-O Ne7
{ While Black's dark-squared bishop is located outside the pawn chain, Black may experience some difficulties with the pin of the knight on f6 after Bc1-g5. That's why it's safer to place the knight on e7. However, Ng8-e7 also contains some other ideas that will be revealed later in the analysis. }
8. Be3 Nd7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Qe2 Ne5
{ Black is fine with retreating back to c6 in case of f2-f4. After that, Black can trade on d4 and advance one of their central pawns to fix the pawn structure or simplify the position in case of a pawn trade. }
