{ Another possible option is to play  9...Nf6  However, in case of 9...Nge7, White's pawn march on the kingside is not so effective as it could be when the knight was on f6. }
10. O-O e5
{ Of course, not the only option for Black.  10...O-O   or  10...Bxe3  were at least two others. However, e6-e5 allows Black to apply typical ideas for these types of positions - to move the knight to d4 and recapture with a pawn in case White captures. This strategy is stronger when White's pawn is on c4, not on c2. But even in this position, it's still fine for Black. }
11. Bxa7 { To prevent Nc6-d4. } 11... Rxa7 12. a4 Be6 13. Bc4 O-O 14. Rad1 Qc7
{ Getting off the d-file to avoid White's opposing rook. } 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16.
Qd3 Nc8
{ Black's position is a bit passive. But the central pawn skeleton compensates for that by preventing White's knights from becoming active. }
*

