1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3
{ 5.Bd3 is a traditional weapon against the Kan Sicilian. This move is quite popular among club players and grandmasters. }
5... Bc5
{ The most playable variation. Black has some other options including  5...g6  but if Black wants to play for a victory, 5...Bc5 is the best choice. Positions that may happen in this line are so complicated that any mistake made by White can result into a winning chance for Black. }
6. Nb3 Ba7
{ 6...Be7  is another popular option, but after  7.Qg4  @@StartBracket@@attacking g7@@EndBracket@@ White gets the initiative and the Black bishop on  e7  is less active than if it was on  a7  . Black sets up an ambush with this bishop on  a7  . }
7. O-O Nc6 8. Qg4 Nf6
{ And Black sacrifices the pawn. Another option in this position is to play  8...Qf6  and protect the pawn. It's much safer, but in that line, Black is unlikely to take over the initiative. }
