[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: 5.Be2"]
[Black "7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. a3
{ Sometimes a2-a3 is a helpful move for White in these types of positions. However, playing it too early may result in a tempo loss, and this is how White shows that they are not going to fight for an opening advantage. }
7... b5
{ 7...Bc5   and  7...Be7  are two other options that offer Black at least an equal position. But since White spent a tempo on a3, Black can fianchetto their light-squared bishop. Qc7 and b5 together without any development is a risky strategy. But if White loses a tempo, it's fine. }
8. f4 Bb7 9. e5 Nd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ Black's light-squared bishop occupied the main diagonal and White has to trade it. }
11. Bf3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nc6
{ White gained some space, but the e5-pawn can be undermined with d7-d6 in the future. If White decides to take on c6, Black captures back with a pawn and gets an approximately equal position with a better bishop. }
*

