[White "Chapter 6: 5.Be2"]
[Black "7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. Be3 Bb4
{ 6.Be3 or 7.Be3 before White's king is castled is a typical inaccuracy that many club players make. Black's immediate reaction is to play Bb4 and put pressure on c3 and e4 simultaneously. }
8. Qd3 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Bxc3+
{ And then White realizes that this bishop can't be captured. } 10. Bd2 Bxd2+
11. Kxd2 Nc6 { with extra material for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: 5.Be2"]
[Black "7.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. Be3 Bb4
{ 6.Be3 or 7.Be3 before White's king is castled is a typical inaccuracy that many club players make. Black's immediate reaction is to play Bb4 and put pressure on c3 and e4 simultaneously. }
8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 d6
{ Instead of playing 9...d6, Black also has two other options:  9...d5   and  9...Nxe4  Both look attractive, but after that White takes over the initiative and Black has to play several exact defensive moves to extinguish the initiative. 9...d6 doesn't go into all these complications but offers Black a better pawn structure. }
10. Qd3 Nbd7
{ Black has several ways to play this position. Of course, d6-d5 can be played, but I recommend you stick to 'The Hedgehog' playing strategy: castle kingside, b7-b6, Bc8-b7, and take advantage of a better pawn structure while blocking the White pawns with knights. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: 5.Be2"]
[Black "7.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. O-O Be7
{ 7...Bb4?!  doesn't make any sense if White's king has already castled. White may play  8.Qd3  or just sacrifice the pawn and obtain the initiative. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 d6
{ to secure the e5-square. We have reached a position where White has five different plans, and Black's plan may vary depending on what White is doing. }
10. g4
{ The most aggressive move. However, if Black plays properly, they'll be able to equalize! }
10... d5
{ 'If someone attacks you on the flank, look for counterplay in the center!' }
11. exd5
{ This way White opens up the position in the center and tries to gain a pawn. However, the kingside pawn march leads to the weak position of the king on g1. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 { White can't ignore Black's knight standing on d5. } 12...
exd5 13. Bd3 Nc6
{ Putting some pressure on d4. If White trades knights on c6, Black is fine with capturing with the b-pawn and reinforcing the center. }
14. Qf3 Bc5 { attacking d4 and intending to trade off White's active pieces. }
15. Qh3 { The d4-knight can't be taken since White threatens a checkmate. }
15... g6
{ with such an open center, White's kingside attack won't succeed. After Black trades at least one pair of minor pieces, the position becomes equal with not enough material for White to support the attack. If  16.Nf5  Black may reply with  16...d4   or  16...Qb6  White's attack here won't succeed while the position is open. }
*

