{ to secure the e5-square. We have reached a position where White has five different plans, and Black's plan may vary depending on what White is doing. }
10. a4 { Preventing Black's b7-b5. } 10... Nc6 11. Kh1 Re8 12. Qe1 Nxd4 13.
Bxd4 e5
{ Another typical move for the Kan Sicilian. Playing e6-e5 without a preliminary trade on d4 could be a mistake due to Nd4-f5 or Nd4xc6 and f4-f5 on the next move. }
14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Qg3 Bd8 16. Be3 Kh8
{ Black has the better pawn structure. The goal is to play Bc8-e6, move the knight out, and play f7-f6 to support the center. White's knight on c3 has to stay there to prevent Black's counterplay on the c-file. But in case of Nc3-d5, Black is happy to trade the light-squared bishop for that knight. }
