1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. O-O Be7
{ 7...Bb4?!  doesn't make any sense if White's king has already castled. White may play  8.Qd3  or just sacrifice the pawn and obtain the initiative. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 d6
{ to secure the e5-square. We have reached a position where White has five different plans, and Black's plan may vary depending on what White is doing. }
10. Kh1 b5 11. a3 Bb7 12. Bd3 Nbd7 13. Qf3 Nc5
{ White has to tie down their queen to the protection of the e4-square. } 14.
Rae1 Rac8 15. Bf2 d5
{ Black had several options in this position. Instead of 15...d5, for example, 15...Nfd7   or  15...Rfd8  can be played. There is no need to hurry. However, if Black is looking for the most simple way of equalization in this variation, then 15...d5 is the best. }
16. e5
{ Of course, taking on d5 can be a mistake for White. This is how Black can activate their light-squared bishop. }
16... Nfe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4
{ White can't accept the enemy knight on e4 and ignore it. } 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19.
Qg3 Bd5
{ The e4-pawn isn't a weakness while Black's light-squared bishop is still on the board. Black has a clear plan - to play f7-f5. If White captures en passant, Black improves their dark-squared bishop, plays e6-e5 to trade the pawns, and tries to set up their play around the passed pawn on e4. If White doesn't capture en passant, Black fixes the position on the kingside and switches to the queenside with a6-a5, Qc7-b7, and b5-b4 breakout. }
