1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. O-O Be7
{ 7...Bb4?!  doesn't make any sense if White's king has already castled. White may play  8.Qd3  or just sacrifice the pawn and obtain the initiative. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 d6
{ to secure the e5-square. We have reached a position where White has five different plans, and Black's plan may vary depending on what White is doing. }
10. Bf3 Nc6 11. Nb3
{ Kind of a tempo loss, but at the same time, White tries to keep the position more complicated. }
11... b5 12. a3 Bb7 13. Qe1 Rac8
{ An approximately equal position. White tries to control the e5-square and signal the kingside attack, while Black has 2 different plans. They can relocate the knight to b6 and c4 or take on c3 and then attack White's ruined queenside pawns. The other idea is to play Nc6-a5, trade knights, simplify the position, and continue attacking the e4-pawn. }
