1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5.Be2  and  6.Nc3  is a classical development among players who prefer to play  Be2  setups against the Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Taimanov. Here Black may play the pure Kan Sicilian move  6...b5  but it's an extremely risky strategy to combine Qc7 & b5 too early, when the kingside pieces are not developed. That's why I recommend playing 6...Qc7 first to develop the kingside, and then continue with b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. Black is likely to achieve Scheveningen positions, but with the queen on c7. }
7. O-O Be7
{ 7...Bb4?!  doesn't make any sense if White's king has already castled. White may play  8.Qd3  or just sacrifice the pawn and obtain the initiative. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 d6
{ to secure the e5-square. We have reached a position where White has five different plans, and Black's plan may vary depending on what White is doing. }
10. a4 { Preventing Black's b7-b5. } 10... Nc6 11. Kh1 Re8
{ The idea of this move is to trade the knights on d4 and play e6-e5 to simplify the position and prevent a future kingside attack. }
12. Bf3
{ The idea of such a move is to prevent Black's development on the queenside and threaten e4-e5 in some variations. }
12... Rb8 13. Qe1 e5
{ Simplifying the position. We usually trade the knights first and then play e5. However, in this position there is no reason to take on  d4  first. Black has a rook on  b8  , that’s why if White decides to trade on  c6  with  14.Nxc6  Black replies with  14...bxc6  and the White pawn on b2 is hanging. So, White doesn't have enough time to play f4-f5, keep the position closed, and continue their kingside attack. }
14. Nde2
{ with the idea to take on f4 with the knight and control the d5-square. }
14... exf4 15. Nxf4 Be6
{ Black is more than happy to exchange their light-squared bishop for the knight, because White's light-squared bishop is bad. In case of a4-a5, Black may reply with Be7-d8 and trade dark-squared bishops. White's kingside attack doesn't look aggressive here due to Be7-f8 and Kg8-h8, cemented with Nc6-e5. }
