[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: 5.Nc3"]
[Black "5.Nc3 with 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. g3 Bb4
{ Nowadays almost every player likes to fianchetto a light-squared bishop and it doesn't really matter if it's a Catalan or the first move was e4 and we have Sicilian on the board. However, the Kan move order copes well with 6.g3. 6...Bb4 should be executed immediately, because this is how Black forces White to start defending their position. }
7. Ne2
{ The most popular move. At first sight, the knight on e2 looks too awkward, but Black should keep in mind that this knight gets a good spot on g3 in case if White plays g3-g4. }
7... Be7
{ There is nothing to do on b4, while there is always the other knight to replace the one on c3. }
8. Bg2 Nf6
{ Black continues their natural piece development. First - kingside pieces, then queenside. }
9. O-O Nc6 10. h3
{ White needs to get more space with h2-h3 and g3-g4 to find a good spot for their e2-knight. }
10... d6
{ To secure the e5-square with the pawn. Black's intention is to play b7-b5 and fianchetto their light-squared bishop. That's why they prepare for White's e4-e5 jab! }
11. g4 b5
{ While White spends time to improve their knight, Black continues their development. }
12. Ng3 Bb7
{ finishing their development. However, this move is also played to support the d5-square. }
13. f4 b4 14. Na4 d5
{ It's too risky for White to capture the d5-pawn due to Ra8-d8. In this position, White's pieces are disorganized and their kingside attack looks inoffensive. }
*

