[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. g3 Bb4
{ Nowadays almost every player likes to fianchetto a light-squared bishop and it doesn't really matter if it's a Catalan or the first move was e4 and we have Sicilian on the board. However, the Kan move order copes well with 6.g3. 6...Bb4 should be executed immediately, because this is how Black forces White to start defending their position. }
7. Bd2 Nf6 { Threatening to gain a pawn. } 8. Bg2 Nc6
{ This is a critical decision. Now White has to either take on c6 or retreat @@StartBracket@@which means losing a tempo@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nxc6 dxc6
{ 9...bxc6  is more common for Kan Sicilian positions, but here Black may apply another plan and take control over the center. }
10. O-O Be7
{ Of course, Black's main idea is to play e6-e5, block White's light-squared bishop, control the center, and release their own light-squared bishop. But this move can't be played right now due to  10...e5  11.Nd5!  Nxd5  12.exd5  Bxd2  13.Qxd2  cxd5  14.Qxd5  and Black is slightly better. }
11. Na4 b5 12. e5 Nd5
{ The e5-pawn wasn't hanging due to the weakness of the c6-pawn. } 13. c4 bxa4
{ There are no squares to escape with the d5-knight. } 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Qxa4+
Bd7 16. Qd4 O-O
{ Black's pawn structure is better and it can offer some practical chances later in the game. Black's plan is to activate the bishops and locate rooks on the b- and c-files to make White's queenside pawns the objects of the attack. }
