14. Qe1 h4
{ The main idea of 13...Bg4 was to prevent White from playing g3-g4. Now Black opens the position. }
15. fxe5 Nh5 16. hxg4 Nxg3+ 17. Kg1 Nxf1
{ Black trades two minor pieces for a rook and pawn. } 18. Qxf1 h3 19. Bxh3 Rd8
20. Be3 Qxe5
{ The bishop on h3 is like a glorified pawn that only prevents queen penetration to the second rank. The position is considered to be equal, but quite sharp. Practically, Black has more chances to succeed due to White's king weakness. }
