1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. Be3 Bb4 7. Ne2
{ White retreats with his knight, but this is how they solve the problem with the weakness on c3. }
7... Nf6 8. a3 Be7
{ Black's dark-squared bishop has nothing to do on b4 while one knight can be replaced by the other one. It's better to keep this bishop to cover the dark squares later in the game. }
9. Na4
{ intending to create a positional grip occupying the dark squares on the queenside. }
9... Nc6 10. Nb6 Rb8
{ Black is happy to trade their light-squared bishop for a knight! } 11. Nc3 d6
12. Be2 Nd7 13. Nca4 Nc5
{ This is how Black solves their problems and gets rid of a knight on b6. If White doesn't take, Nc5xa4, Nb6xa4 and b5 with tempo comes next. }
14. Nxc5 dxc5 15. Nxc8 Rxc8
{ White has the bishop pair, but Black has no weaknesses in their position. Moreover, the light-squared bishop for knight exchange was favorable for Black! }
