1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to focus on the kingside attack later in the game. }
6... Nf6 7. f4 d6 8. Qf3 b5
{ Black prepares to occupy the main diagonal with Bc8-b7. } 9. g4 Bb7 10. Be3
Nfd7 11. O-O-O b4
{ At this stage of the game, the move doesn't allow White to play any other plan than the one shown in this variation. If Black played  11...Nc5  instead of 11... b4, White could play  12.a3  to prevent Black from playing b5-b4. }
12. Nce2 Nc5 13. Kb1 Nbd7 14. g5
{ In this position, Black has a wide choice of several approximately equal options: 1@@EndBracket@@ O-O-O to avoid attacks on opposite castled positions and continue playing strategically, 2@@EndBracket@@ Rc8 to have the rook join the attack, 3@@EndBracket@@ g6 with the idea to fianchetto a dark-squared bishop, while White is unable to attack the d6-pawn. }
14... g6 15. h4 h5 { Fixing the pawn structure on the kingside. } 16. gxh6
O-O-O
{ Black takes the h-pawn and activates their bishop on the next move. However, the theater of war is located in the center and on the queenside in this position. }
