1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to focus on the kingside attack later in the game. }
6... Nf6 7. Qe2 d6 { A natural move to parry White's e4-e5 threat. } 8. f4 Nbd7
9. g4 Nc5 10. g5 Nfd7
{ White gained some space on the kingside preparing a future attack on the Black king. However, Black keeps their position flexible for any breakout either in the center or on the kingside. }
11. Bd2 g6
{ According to the database statistics, a kingside fianchetto is the only way to provide Black with counterplay in this position. }
12. f5 Ne5
{ Looks like White squeezed his opponent, but at the same time despite a lack of space, Black can successfully finish their development intending to play Bc8-d7, Ra8-c8. Moreover, while the dark-squared bishop is still on f8, Black keeps in mind an option to play h7-h6 and activate it from the other side. }
