1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to focus on the kingside attack later in the game. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O d6
{ A natural response that allows Black to stay flexible to any plan that White can potentially apply in this position. }
8. a4 b6 9. f4 Bb7 10. Qe2 Nbd7
{ White played Qe2 to threaten to play e4-e5 at some favorable moment. However, Black can play with the d-knight to c5 and relocate the other knight to d7. }
11. f5
{ 11.Kh1  and Bd2 with the idea to play Rae1 are analyzed in the 8.Kh1 line. }
11... e5
{ The best but typical response to f5. This is how Black relieves tension, gains a tempo, and continues their development. }
12. Nf3 Be7 13. Bg5 O-O 14. Nd2 Rfe8
{ Protecting the bishop on e7 and hoping to play d6-d5 and activate the rook on the e-file. }
15. Kh1 d5 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. exd5 Bb4
{ Intending to trade a dark-squared bishop for the knight. Usually in the Kan Sicilian, Black prefers to keep their dark-squared bishop on the board to cover weaknesses in their camp. However, in this position, the pawn structure changed a lot and this bishop became not so important. }
18. Nde4 Bxc3 19. Nxc3 e4 20. Bc4 Rad8
{ Black activates the last piece and wants to trade the a6-pawn for the d5-pawn. }
21. Bxa6 Bxa6 22. Qxa6 Nxd5 23. Nxd5 Rxd5 { With clear play for Black. } *

