1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ 5...b5  is another popular option for Black nowadays. However, this option is considered risky compared to the classical 5...Qc7, which places the queen on a normal 'Kan' square. From c7, it attacks the e5-square and potentially participates into the attack on the c-file. }
6. Bd3
{ The idea of this move is to focus on the kingside attack later in the game. }
6... Nf6 7. O-O d6
{ A natural response that allows Black to stay flexible to any plan that White can potentially apply in this position. }
8. Kh1 Nbd7 9. f4 Be7
{ Just one step left to castle. At the same time, Black doesn't apply any active actions expecting White to play Qd1-e2. }
10. Qe2 Nc5
{ Black intends to trade the knight for the bishop. However, while the bishop has no option to escape, Black shouldn't rush the position and initiate a trade immediately.  10...b5  and 11...Bb7 is another possible plan for Black in this position. However, after 10...b5, Black can fall into the attack of their b5-pawn after  11.b4  and 12.a4. }
11. Bd2 O-O 12. b4 { is probably the most promising move for white } 12... Nxd3
13. cxd3
{ On one hand, the exchange on d3 reinforced White's center. On the other hand, it's difficult to attack the kingside without a light-squared bishop. }
13... Qb6
{ Attacking the knight and the b4-pawn simultaneously. However, while the dark-squared bishop is on d2, the b4-pawn is poisoned. }
14. Nb3 Bd7 15. a3 Rfc8
{ Black prepares to get his queen to d8 if needed. Black is in a stationary state expecting further actions from White. However, strategically Black is better due to the bishop pair. If Black is able to transition into the endgame or open the position, they can play for a victory. }
