8. Kh1 Nbd7 9. f4 Be7
{ Just one step left to castle. At the same time, Black doesn't apply any active actions expecting White to play Qd1-e2. }
10. Qe2 Nc5
{ Black intends to trade the knight for the bishop. However, while the bishop has no option to escape, Black shouldn't rush the position and initiate a trade immediately.  10...b5  and 11...Bb7 is another possible plan for Black in this position. However, after 10...b5, Black can fall into the attack of their b5-pawn after  11.b4  and 12.a4. }
11. Bd2 O-O 12. Rae1 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 b5 14. e5 Ne8
{ 14...Nd7  was also possible, but then  15.Qg3  and White keeps the control over the center while simultaneously adding some pressure on the g-file. }
15. Ne4 Bb7
{ Black can always trade their light-squared bishop for the knight on e4 and simplify the position. In such a case, the e8-knight should be relocated to c7 and d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Alapin Smith-Morra"]
[Black "Smith-Morra #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ This is how White wants to play the Smith-Morra Gambit. This opening is played not so often at the GM level, but is very common for club players. And, of course, there are several good continuations for Black that lead to a safe position, sometimes even with an extra pawn. For example, Black may choose to play  3...dxc3  4.Nxc3  Nc6  5.Nf3  d6  6.Bc4  a6  7.O-O  Nf6  with an extra pawn, but some initiative for White.   or  3...dxc3  4.Nxc3  Nc6  5.Nf3  e6  6.Bc4  Nge7  that NM Logozar suggested @@StartBracket@@this variation is also published at Chessable@@EndBracket@@. However, both these lines require much knowledge. That's why, in this course, FM Viktor Neustroev suggests not to accept the pawn sacrifice, but to transpose to the Alapin Variation. This transposition of moves is often used at the master level and above. However, it is not so popular among club players. Therefore, Black gets more practical chances to succeed while forcing White to play the Alapin Variation @@StartBracket@@the opening that they are not familiar with@@EndBracket@@ instead of playing the Smith-Morra @@StartBracket@@the line that they prepared for the game@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ Now Black may accept the Smith-Morra, because White's bishop will be on d3 and White has to spend another tempo on its improvement. }
4... dxc3 5. Nxc3 Nc6 { The main idea here is to prevent e4-e5. } 6. Bg5 e6
{ Black doesn't want doubled pawns if the bishop takes the knight on f6. } 7.
Nf3 d6 8. Qe2 h6
{ This is how Black tries to solve all their problems and then realize their extra pawn. }
9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5
{ Black trades their knight for the bishop, fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop, and finishes their development. }
*

