[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Alapin Smith-Morra"]
[Black "Alapin with 7.Bc4 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin Variation is a common weapon against the Sicilian Defense for those who don't want to learn much  theory or prefer a more positional playing style. }
2... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4
{ White may vary the move order: 4.d4, 4.Bc4 and 4.Nf3 can be played as well and all lead to the same line. Deviations from the main line only favor Black. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. cxd4 e6
{ 6...e6 is one of the main options for Black.  6...d6  is another popular option, for example. But if Black decides to follow the Kan Sicilian, they may reach this position with an absolutely different move order. That's why it's highly recommended to stick to the same strategy every time. A high-level player, of course, may learn several possible lines here and vary them from time to time. }
7. Bc4 d6
{ This is the main position of the Alapin Variation and it can happen with a different move order. }
8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qa5
{ Black's queen on a5 is not the object of the attack, vacates the d8-square for the f-rook, and pressures the e5- and c3-pawns. }
13. Rb1 Rd8
{ Taking the  c3  pawn is too risky due to  13...Qxc3  14.Bd2  Qa3  15.Rfc1  with an initiative for White. }
14. Rb5 Qc7 { The queen would be trapped in case of  14...Qxc3  15.Bb2 } 15.
Bd3 b6 { Black is threatening Bc8-a6. } 16. Rb1 Bb7
{ Black finished their development and now takes advantage of a better pawn structure, while White's activity is restricted. For example,  17.Qe4  is met with  17...g6 }
*

