[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Kan vs Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind with 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
{ Maroczy Bind is considered to be one of the strongest continuations against the Kan Sicilian. }
5... Nf6
{ Usually we start with Qc7 to secure the e5-square, but in this position, White can't play e4-e5. Black replies with Qa5+ and captures the pawn for free. }
6. Nc3
{ Now Qc7 has to be played. White is threatening with e4-e5. Another option in this position is  6...Bb4  However, White can then play  7.Qd3  which leads to playable, but slightly better position for White. }
6... Qc7 7. Be3 Bb4 8. f3 O-O 9. Rc1 d5
{ The c3-knight is pinned. That's why there will be no discovered attack on the queen on c7. d7-d5 not only simplifies the position, but opens it and allows Black to take the advantage of their lead in development. }
10. cxd5 exd5 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Rxc3 Qe5
{ Black doesn't experience any problems with development of their pieces and at the same time puts pressure on the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Kan vs Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind with 7.Be3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
{ Maroczy Bind is considered to be one of the strongest continuations against the Kan Sicilian. }
5... Nf6
{ Usually we start with Qc7 to secure the e5-square, but in this position, White can't play e4-e5. Black replies with Qa5+ and captures the pawn for free. }
6. Nc3
{ Now Qc7 has to be played. White is threatening with e4-e5. Another option in this position is  6...Bb4  However, White can then play  7.Qd3  which leads to playable, but slightly better position for White. }
6... Qc7 7. Be3 Bb4 8. Bd3 Bxc3+ { Ruining White's pawn structure. } 9. bxc3 d6
{ Black intends to play Nb8-d7, b7-b6, and Bc8-b7 or Nb8-d7-c5, e6-e5, and Bc8-e6. }
10. O-O Nbd7 11. f4 b6
{ Instead of taking time to castle, Black speeds up development for the light-squared bishop to increase pressure on e4. }
12. Nb3 Bb7 13. Qc2 e5
{ weakens the d5-square, but it's almost impossible to deliver the White knight there. Please note that e6-e5 is played when Nd4-f5 is unavailable for White. Black intends to finish their development after O-O and start some active actions with their knights. White's light-squared bishop is a glorified pawn. It holds White's position together. And Black even has a choice to trade one of the knights for this bishop. In such a case, the e4- and c4-pawns can become the objects of an attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: Kan vs Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind with 7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
{ Maroczy Bind is considered to be one of the strongest continuations against the Kan Sicilian. }
5... Nf6
{ Usually we start with Qc7 to secure the e5-square, but in this position, White can't play e4-e5. Black replies with Qa5+ and captures the pawn for free. }
6. Nc3
{ Now Qc7 has to be played. White is threatening with e4-e5. Another option in this position is  6...Bb4  However, White can then play  7.Qd3  which leads to playable, but slightly better position for White. }
6... Qc7 7. a3 { A tricky move that prevents Black from playing 7...Bb4. } 7...
b6
{ In this position, Black has a choice: to play 'The Hedgehog' with 7...b6 or to play  7...Nxe4  with 8...Qe5 gaining a piece back. Of course, 7...Nxe4 looks attractive and can be played even on the top level as GM Levan Pantsulaia demonstrated in his games. White is obviously better if they play properly, but the position is very complicated and that's why this variation deserves the right to exist! }
8. Be3 Bb7
{ White's move order can be different. But Black should first develop the bishop to  b7  to force White to play  9.f3  and prevent them from playing f2-f4. }
9. Bd3 Nc6
{ 9.Bd3 was played to support the e4-pawn and play f2-f4 in the future. That's why Black's strategy with the passive 'hedgehog' formation won't work and we have to play more aggressively. }
10. Rc1 Ne5
{ But at least Black can trade his knight for a bishop and hope to exploit his bishop pair in the future. }
*

