1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
{ Maroczy Bind is considered to be one of the strongest continuations against the Kan Sicilian. }
5... Nf6
{ Usually we start with Qc7 to secure the e5-square, but in this position, White can't play e4-e5. Black replies with Qa5+ and captures the pawn for free. }
6. Nc3
{ Now Qc7 has to be played. White is threatening with e4-e5. Another option in this position is  6...Bb4  However, White can then play  7.Qd3  which leads to playable, but slightly better position for White. }
6... Qc7 7. Bd3 { Inaccuracy! The d-file is overloaded. } 7... Nc6
{ Forcing White to trade the knights or play Be3 to protect it. If White's knight retreats, it can be regarded as a tempo loss. }
8. Be3 Ne5 9. Rc1 Nfg4
{ White's dark-squared bishop is more important. And of course, the c4-pawn wasn't hanging due to a discovered attack on the c-file. }
10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Ne5 { A double attack. } 13. Qd1 Qxc4 14. Nd5
Nd3+ 15. Qxd3 Qxc1+ { But not  15...Qxd3  because of  16.Nc7# } 16. Ke2 Qxb2+
17. Kf3 exd5 { with a lot of extra material. } *

