1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
{ Maroczy Bind is considered to be one of the strongest continuations against the Kan Sicilian. }
5... Nf6
{ Usually we start with Qc7 to secure the e5-square, but in this position, White can't play e4-e5. Black replies with Qa5+ and captures the pawn for free. }
6. Nc3
{ Now Qc7 has to be played. White is threatening with e4-e5. Another option in this position is  6...Bb4  However, White can then play  7.Qd3  which leads to playable, but slightly better position for White. }
6... Qc7 7. Be2 Bb4 8. Nc2 Bxc3+
{ Another option is to play 8.Be7 and play the 'hedgehog', but why not capture on c3 to double the pawns and then get a flexible pawn center? }
9. bxc3 d6
{ To secure the e5- and c5-squares.  9...Nxe4?  is a mistake due to  10.Qd4  attacking the knight and the g7-pawn. After the knight retreats, White gets the initiative with 11.Bf4. }
10. Ba3 Nxe4 { With ...d6 already played, Black now can take the d4-pawn. } 11.
Qd4 f5 { Black's queen joins the defense. } 12. Bh5+ Kf8 13. Bf3 Nc6 14. Qd1
Nc5
{ Black is one pawn up, but lost their castling privilege. However, if Black makes an artificial castle or at least releases the h-rook, White will have no compensation for the pawn. }
